ThinkPart(
    type='think',
    think='`ProfileModule` imports `AuthModule` and `TypeOrmModule.forFeature([U
serPhotoEntity])`. But it also needs `UserProfileEntity` repository. However, `A
uthModule` exports `TypeOrmModule` (from `AuthModule` exports: `[AuthService, Ty
peOrmModule]`). And `AuthModule` imports `TypeOrmModule.forFeature([UserEntity, 
UserProfileEntity])`. So `ProfileModule` can get `UserProfileEntity` repository 
through `AuthModule`. This is a bit tight coupling but works.\n\nWait, `AuthModu
le` exports `TypeOrmModule`. That means any module importing `AuthModule` gets a
ccess to the repositories registered in `AuthModule`\'s `TypeOrmModule.forFeatur
e`. This is a known NestJS pattern. So `ProfileService` can inject `UserProfileE
ntity` repository because `AuthModule` provides it. This is okay, but maybe not 
ideal. The PRD didn\'t specify this. However, `nestjs.md` says "模块之间通过 Int
erface / EventEmitter 解耦，禁止直接 import 其他模块的内部 Service". It says "禁
止直接 import 其他模块的内部 Service". Importing the whole `AuthModule` is allow
ed? It imports the module, not a service directly. But `AuthModule` is not reall
y a shared module for user/profile entities. A better approach would be to have 
a `UsersModule` or `DatabaseModule`. But given the existing structure, it\'s a m
inor issue.\n\nHowever, `ProfileModule` only imports `UserPhotoEntity` in its ow
n `TypeOrmModule.forFeature`. It relies on `AuthModule` for `UserProfileEntity` 
and `UserEntity`. This might be okay but let\'s note it.\n\nNow let\'s check the
unit test spec for profile service to see if it covers key logic.',
    encrypted=None
)
